				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The easiest way to get PAL60 would probably be to get an RGB NES and rig up an RGB to PAL encoder.<br /><br />Here's how it was done in the real world: PAL-M is a variant of PAL60 with a lower color burst frequency that fits better into the &quot;M&quot; band plan used with NTSC. Brazil used it before the 2007 digital switchover. The NES sold in Brazil had an NTSC PPU and a daughterboard that decoded NTSC and encoded PAL-M. Some sets support both PAL-M and PAL60; others don't.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

